// Section 4: Research and Supporting Evidence

= Research and Supporting Evidence

== Types of Evidence

This project's documentation draws on multiple types of evidence:

/ Primary written sources: Period treatises by practicing craftsmen
  describing tools, materials, and techniques from firsthand experience.
  These include Theophilus Presbyter's _De Diversis Artibus_ (c. 1100–1120)
  @theophilus, Benvenuto Cellini's _Trattati dell'oreficeria_ (1560s)
  @cellini-treatises, and Abraham Bosse's _Traité des manières de graver en
  taille douce_ (1645, documenting practices unchanged from the 16th
  century) @bosse-traite.

/ Extant objects: Surviving engraved copper plates, prints pulled from those
  plates, engraved niello silverwork, and engraved decorative metalwork held
  in major museum collections (Metropolitan Museum of Art, British Museum,
  Rijksmuseum, Victoria and Albert Museum, Bargello). These provide direct
  physical evidence of period materials, techniques, and subjects.

/ Visual documentation: Abraham Bosse's engraved illustrations of the
  engraver's workshop (1643–45) @bosse-traite, the Diderot Encyclopédie
  plates on "Gravure en taille-douce" (c. 1767–1771, documenting practices
  unchanged from the 16th century) @diderot-encyclopedie, and period
  depictions of goldsmith workshops.

/ Modern scholarly analysis: Museum publications, art-historical
  scholarship, and technical analyses of period engravings. Key sources
  include the Metropolitan Museum's Heilbrunn Timeline of Art History essays
  on engraving @met-thompson-engraving, the National Gallery of Art's
  exhibition catalogs @nga-tintoretto-conversion, and the standard
  art-historical treatments of the Renaissance print by Landau and Parshall
  @landau-parshall, Hind @hind-history-engraving, and Griffiths
  @griffiths-prints.

/ Practitioner knowledge: Modern hand engravers who practice period
  techniques, documented in specialized forums (the Engraver's Cafe
  @engraverscafe-homemade @engraverscafe-my-own @engraverscafe-geometry
  @engraverscafe-practice) and instructional materials. While modern, these
  practitioners preserve and transmit technical knowledge about hand-tool
  geometry, sharpening, and cutting technique that is directly continuous
  with period practice.

== Discussion of Sources and Historic Context

The practice of push engraving on copper for the production of devotional
prints emerged from the European goldsmithing trade in the 1430s. Landau
and Parshall locate the origin of intaglio engraving along the Upper Rhine
in southwestern Germany in the 1430s, growing out of goldsmiths' decorative
techniques on metal, and trace the goldsmith-to-engraver transition and the
material practices of the early intaglio shops in detail (ch. 1)
@landau-parshall; the same trajectory is described in Hind's classic
_A History of Engraving and Etching_ (chs. I–II) @hind-history-engraving.
Landau and Parshall further note that the notable engravers of the fifteenth
century were either goldsmiths themselves (Master E.S.) or the sons of
goldsmiths (Martin Schongauer, Albrecht Dürer), and that the technique had
long been used by goldsmiths on their own metal pieces before any impressions
were taken from them @landau-parshall. Antony Griffiths's
_Prints and Printmaking_ likewise locates the origins of European engraving
in the workshop practices of fifteenth-century goldsmiths @griffiths-prints.

The Italian tradition developed simultaneously from niello work. The
standard scholarly catalogue of early Italian engraving — Levenson,
Oberhuber, and Sheehan's _Early Italian Engravings from the National Gallery
of Art_ — documents how the very earliest Italian engraved prints were
impressions taken from silver plates intended for niello, before the niello
fill was added (pp. 528–529) @levenson-early-italian-engravings; Landau and
Parshall give the same account (pp. 26, 67–68) @landau-parshall. Vasari,
in the _Life of Marcantonio Bolognese_ in the 1568 edition of the _Vite_,
credits Maso Finiguerra (1426–1464) with the invention of copperplate
printmaking from impressions of niello plates @vasari-bondanella;
A. Hyatt Mayor's _Prints and People_ gives the modern reassessment of this
account, showing that Finiguerra was one of several Florentine goldsmiths
working in the same niello-print tradition rather than its sole inventor
@mayor-prints-people.

The earliest and most important primary source on medieval metalworking
tools and techniques is Theophilus Presbyter's _De Diversis Artibus_.
C. R. Dodwell's critical edition introduces the _De Diversis Artibus_ as
the most exhaustive surviving account of medieval craft technique, written
by a Benedictine monk who was himself a practicing metalworker
@dodwell-theophilus. The identification of Theophilus with Roger of
Helmarshausen — a goldsmith whose surviving metalwork demonstrates the
techniques described in the text — was first proposed by Albert Ilg in
1874 and developed by Dodwell in his 1961 critical edition; Dodwell himself
treats the identification with caution, writing that the Benedictine
monk-author "may have been" Roger @dodwell-theophilus.

Abraham Bosse's 1645 _Traité des manières de graver en taille douce_ is the
first published treatise specifically on engraving @bosse-traite. While
published just after the period boundary, it documents practices and tools
that were functionally unchanged from the previous century, as the burin,
the sandbag cushion, the sharpening methods, and the printing process it
illustrates are all attested in earlier sources and extant objects. The
treatise was widely translated and remained the standard reference for over
a century.
